# Golden Q&A set for RAGAS evaluation.
# One JSON object per line. Lines starting with '#' are ignored.
# Keep this set small (~15-25 items) and high-quality — it's run on every CI invocation.
{"question": "What are the main advantages of transformer architectures over LSTMs for short-term electricity load forecasting?", "reference_answer": "Transformer architectures avoid the sequential bottleneck of LSTMs and can model long-range dependencies through self-attention, often yielding better accuracy on multi-step horizons. They also parallelise better during training.", "expected_arxiv_ids": []}
{"question": "Which calendar features are most commonly used as exogenous inputs in day-ahead electricity demand forecasting?", "reference_answer": "Hour of day, day of week, month, indicator of weekends, and public holidays are the most common calendar features. Cyclic (sine/cosine) encodings of hour and month are also widely used.", "expected_arxiv_ids": []}
{"question": "What is a typical MAPE range for state-of-the-art day-ahead load forecasting models on national-scale grids?", "reference_answer": "State-of-the-art models typically achieve MAPE in the 1.5–3% range on mature, national-scale systems (e.g. ENTSO-E countries, CAISO), depending on the horizon and the presence of renewables volatility.", "expected_arxiv_ids": []}
{"question": "How is probabilistic forecasting usually evaluated for electricity demand?", "reference_answer": "Probabilistic forecasts are evaluated with proper scoring rules, primarily the continuous ranked probability score (CRPS), pinball loss at a set of target quantiles, and interval coverage / Winkler score.", "expected_arxiv_ids": []}
{"question": "Why is anomaly detection important in electricity load data pipelines?", "reference_answer": "Anomalies (sensor glitches, storms, strikes, COVID-style shocks) contaminate training data and corrupt forecasts. Detecting and flagging them lets the pipeline down-weight or remove them before fitting, preserving model quality.", "expected_arxiv_ids": []}
{"question": "What role do weather features (temperature, humidity) play in short-term load forecasting?", "reference_answer": "Temperature is the single most important exogenous driver — heating in winter and cooling in summer are primary demand sinks. Humidity and wind chill refine the cooling/heating signal, and solar irradiance is used when net load (after PV) is the target.", "expected_arxiv_ids": []}
{"question": "What is the main challenge when applying deep learning models to short time series?", "reference_answer": "Deep learning models typically need large amounts of training data to outperform simpler statistical or gradient-boosting baselines. On short series (<1–2 years) they overfit and lose to classical methods unless strongly regularised or transfer-learned.", "expected_arxiv_ids": []}
{"question": "How can Isolation Forest be used in the context of energy time series?", "reference_answer": "Isolation Forest flags observations that are easy to isolate in feature space via random partitioning. Applied to enriched load data (with lags, rolling stats and calendar features), it detects both point and contextual anomalies without needing labels.", "expected_arxiv_ids": []}
{"question": "What is the Medallion architecture in the context of energy data pipelines?", "reference_answer": "The Medallion architecture organises data into three Delta Lake layers: Bronze (raw, append-only), Silver (cleaned and typed, quality-flagged), and Gold (purpose-built features / marts ready for ML). It's a common Databricks pattern.", "expected_arxiv_ids": []}
{"question": "What is the purpose of a model signature when registering an ML model?", "reference_answer": "A model signature declares the expected input schema (column names and types) and output schema of the model. Registries (e.g. MLflow, Unity Catalog) use it to validate inference-time payloads and to serve the model via REST with strong typing.", "expected_arxiv_ids": []}
